00:13:47,774 --> 00:13:50,902
There is no escapologist,
and I keep telling you I didn't do it.

247
00:13:50,985 --> 00:13:53,570
[indistinct chatter on TV]

248
00:13:55,156 --> 00:13:58,951
[Matilda] Escapologist… Escapologist…

249
00:13:59,035 --> 00:14:02,038
Once upon a time,
there was a great escapologist.

250
00:14:02,621 --> 00:14:04,039
He was so kind.

251
00:14:04,123 --> 00:14:07,168
The sort of man any child
would love to have as their father.

252
00:14:08,669 --> 00:14:11,505
And one day he fell in love with…

253
00:14:12,172 --> 00:14:13,882
an acrobat.

254
00:14:31,775 --> 00:14:32,775
[Mrs. Phelps] Matilda?

255
00:14:35,070 --> 00:14:36,612
Hello, Mrs. Phelps!

256
00:14:36,696 --> 00:14:39,532
School doesn't start
for another hour yet, does it?

257
00:14:40,158 --> 00:14:43,911
Oh, I'm early because of… excitement.

258
00:14:45,330 --> 00:14:47,790
Miss Honey's gonna
teach us to tell stories.

259
00:14:48,541 --> 00:14:50,376
But I think I've got one already.

260
00:14:51,126 --> 00:14:54,338
I can feel it sort of wriggling in me.

261
00:14:54,422 --> 00:14:58,425
-Like it's bursting to get out.
-Well, I think if it's bursting,

262
00:14:58,509 --> 00:15:01,511
you should probably
tell it as soon as possible, don't you?

263
00:15:01,596 --> 00:15:03,138
I'll get us some lemonade.

264
00:15:03,222 --> 00:15:06,391
But it might be a bit… intense.

265
00:15:07,601 --> 00:15:12,106
Matilda Wormwood, stories are my business.
I think I'll be fine.

266
00:15:14,191 --> 00:15:15,525
[Matilda] Once upon a time,

267
00:15:16,110 --> 00:15:19,446
the two greatest circus performers
in the world…

268
00:15:19,529 --> 00:15:24,868
an escapologist, who could
escape from any lock ever invented,

269
00:15:24,951 --> 00:15:27,662
and an acrobat, who was so skilled,

270
00:15:27,746 --> 00:15:30,123
it seemed she could actually fly,

271
00:15:30,206 --> 00:15:32,792
-fell in love and got married.
-[slurping]

272
00:15:32,876 --> 00:15:37,338
Together they performed the most
incredible feats anyone had ever seen.

273
00:15:37,964 --> 00:15:40,049
People would come from miles around.

274
00:15:40,133 --> 00:15:43,552
Kings, queens, celebrities and astronauts.

275
00:15:44,303 --> 00:15:46,848
But despite their love,

276
00:15:46,931 --> 00:15:50,434
despite their fame, they were sad.

277
00:15:50,518 --> 00:15:54,563
"We have everything that
the world has to offer," said the wife.

278
00:15:54,647 --> 00:15:57,566
"But not the one thing in the world
we want most.

279
00:15:58,526 --> 00:15:59,860
We do not have a child."

280
00:15:59,943 --> 00:16:01,570
"Patience my love,"

281
00:16:01,654 --> 00:16:04,907
the husband replied.
"Time is on our side.

282
00:16:04,990 --> 00:16:06,909
Even time loves us."

283
00:16:07,701 --> 00:16:10,954
But time is the one thing
no one is master of.

284
00:16:11,539 --> 00:16:15,250
And as time passed,
they grew quite old and still,

285
00:16:15,333 --> 00:16:16,544
no child.

286
00:16:17,252 --> 00:16:20,756
The sadness of living alone
in their big, empty house

287
00:16:20,839 --> 00:16:23,676
drew them on to ever more dangerous feats,

288
00:16:23,759 --> 00:16:28,513
as work became the only place to escape
the inescapable sorrow of their lives.

289
00:16:28,596 --> 00:16:30,182
[yelling]

290
00:16:30,265 --> 00:16:32,559
And so it was, they decided to perform

291
00:16:32,642 --> 00:16:36,188
the most dangerous feat
ever in the world, ever!

292
00:16:36,271 --> 00:16:37,647
It is called…

293
00:16:37,730 --> 00:16:38,815
Said the acrobat,

294
00:16:38,898 --> 00:16:41,109
announcing the event to the world's press,

295
00:16:41,193 --> 00:16:44,070
who had gathered to listen
with bated breath.

296
00:16:44,153 --> 00:16:47,407
The Burning Woman Hurling Through the Air

297
00:16:47,490 --> 00:16:49,576
With Dynamite in Her Hair

298
00:16:49,659 --> 00:16:52,662
Over Sharks and Spiky Objects…

299
00:16:52,745 --> 00:16:56,248
Caught by the Man Locked in the Cage and…

300
00:16:56,332 --> 00:17:01,170
[both] …it is the most dangerous feat
ever in the world ever!

301
00:17:02,046 --> 00:17:03,589
[shouting questions]

302
00:17:07,343 --> 00:17:08,845
It is our destiny.

303
00:17:09,803 --> 00:17:12,181
It is where the loneliness of life
has led us.

304
00:17:13,765 --> 00:17:15,767
[bell tolling faintly]

305
00:17:17,103 --> 00:17:19,605
Well, what happened next?

306
00:17:21,022 --> 00:17:22,899
I… I don't know.

307
00:17:23,942 --> 00:17:25,569
Not yet, anyway.

308
00:17:26,152 --> 00:17:27,779
School's open. I'd better go.

309
00:17:28,364 --> 00:17:29,698
But what about the rest of the story?

310
00:17:29,781 --> 00:17:31,199
I'll tell you the rest tomorrow.

311
00:17:31,282 --> 00:17:33,910
Tomorrow?
But I'm over at the lake tomorrow.

312
00:17:33,994 --> 00:17:34,953
[Matilda] The lake, okay.

313
00:17:35,036 --> 00:17:37,413
Well, have a great day at school.

314
00:17:37,497 --> 00:17:39,625
And… be careful in there.

315
00:17:39,708 --> 00:17:41,542
Oh, I'm not worried.

316
00:17:41,626 --> 00:17:45,380
If people do scary things to you,
you can just do scary things back.

317
00:17:45,463 --> 00:17:47,715
[Mrs. Phelps] But Matilda, remember,

318
00:17:48,341 --> 00:17:50,135
two wrongs don't make a right.

319
00:17:50,218 --> 00:17:51,511
Unless they do.

320
00:17:51,594 --> 00:17:54,389
In which case you've just made
a right out of two wrongs.

321
00:17:54,472 --> 00:17:55,848
Which has got to be good!

322
00:18:00,978 --> 00:18:02,397
[children chattering]

323
00:18:02,480 --> 00:18:04,774
Is it your first day too?

324
00:18:04,857 --> 00:18:09,111
Yes, I'm not worried,
but I think Isaac might be.

325
00:18:10,780 --> 00:18:12,364
What if we went in together?

326
00:18:13,407 --> 00:18:17,536
Yep! That way me and Isaac
can look after you if anything…

327
00:18:17,620 --> 00:18:18,621
You know.

328
00:18:18,704 --> 00:18:19,914
[metal clanging]

329
00:18:21,040 --> 00:18:23,793
[crows cawing]

330
00:18:29,506 --> 00:18:30,549
[girl] Oi, new kids!

331
00:18:31,967 --> 00:18:35,512
♪ And so you think you're able
To survive this mess ♪

332
00:18:35,595 --> 00:18:39,808
♪ By being a prince or a princess
You will soon see ♪

333
00:18:39,891 --> 00:18:42,394
♪ There's no escaping tragedy ♪

334
00:18:44,563 --> 00:18:48,983
♪ And even
If you put in heaps of effort ♪

335
00:18:49,067 --> 00:18:51,820
♪ You're just wasting energy ♪

336
00:18:51,903 --> 00:18:56,282
♪ 'Cause your life as you know
It is ancient history ♪

337
00:18:56,365 --> 00:18:57,283
-[metal banging]
-[both gasp]

338
00:18:57,366 --> 00:19:00,954
[all] ♪ I have suffered in this jail ♪

339
00:19:01,037 --> 00:19:03,664
♪ I've been trapped inside
This cage for ages ♪

340
00:19:03,747 --> 00:19:05,249
♪ This living 'ell ♪

341
00:19:05,333 --> 00:19:07,835
♪ But if I try I can remember ♪

342
00:19:07,919 --> 00:19:10,379
♪ Back before my life had ended ♪

343
00:19:10,463 --> 00:19:13,132
♪ Before my happy days were over ♪

344
00:19:13,216 --> 00:19:17,178
♪ Before I first heard
The pealing of the bell ♪

345
00:19:17,261 --> 00:19:19,597
♪ Like you, I was curious ♪

346
00:19:19,680 --> 00:19:22,266
♪ So innocent I asked
A thousand questions ♪

347
00:19:22,350 --> 00:19:24,477
♪ But unless you want to suffer ♪

348
00:19:24,560 --> 00:19:27,646
♪ Listen up and I will teach you
A thing or two ♪

349
00:19:27,730 --> 00:19:29,272
♪ You listen here, my dear ♪

350
00:19:29,356 --> 00:19:31,316
♪ You'll be punished so severely
If you step out of line ♪

351
00:19:31,399 --> 00:19:34,402
♪ And if you cry it will be double
You should stay out of trouble ♪

352
00:19:34,486 --> 00:19:36,697
♪ And remember to be extremely careful ♪

353
00:19:37,906 --> 00:19:38,991
Why?

354
00:19:39,074 --> 00:19:40,242
♪ Why? ♪

355
00:19:40,325 --> 00:19:42,535
Why? Did you hear what we said?

356
00:19:44,371 --> 00:19:47,082
♪ Just you wait for Phys-Ed ♪

357
00:19:47,582 --> 00:19:48,750
What's Phys-Ed?

358
00:19:49,334 --> 00:19:50,252
Physical Education.

359
00:19:51,169 --> 00:19:52,879
[all] The Trunchbull speciality.

360
00:19:53,921 --> 00:19:55,089
Who are you?

361
00:19:55,173 --> 00:19:57,967
We're prefects.
We're here to take you to class.

362
00:19:58,050 --> 00:19:59,927
So we're going to start learning?

363
00:20:00,011 --> 00:20:01,638
Oh, you'll start learning, all right.

364
00:20:01,721 --> 00:20:03,931
Great, I already know the alphabet.

365
00:20:04,474 --> 00:20:07,519
You don't know the alphabet
until we learn you the alphabet.

366
00:20:09,562 --> 00:20:11,355
♪ And so you think you're able ♪

367
00:20:11,438 --> 00:20:14,651
♪ To survive this mess
By being a prince or a princess ♪

368
00:20:14,734 --> 00:20:18,529
♪ You will soon see
There's no escaping tragedy ♪

369
00:20:20,406 --> 00:20:23,784
♪ And even
If you put in heaps of effort ♪

370
00:20:23,868 --> 00:20:25,827
♪ You're just wasting energy ♪

371
00:20:26,412 --> 00:20:29,456
♪ 'Cause your life as you know it
Is ancient history ♪

372
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:34,628
♪ I have suffered in this jail ♪

373
00:20:34,711 --> 00:20:37,881
♪ I've been trapped
Inside this cage for ages ♪

374
00:20:37,964 --> 00:20:39,800
♪ This living 'ell ♪

375
00:20:39,883 --> 00:20:42,260
♪ But if I try I can remember ♪

376
00:20:42,344 --> 00:20:44,721
♪ Back before my life had ended ♪

377
00:20:44,805 --> 00:20:47,474
♪ Before my happy days were over ♪

378
00:20:47,558 --> 00:20:51,853
♪ Before I first heard
The pealing of the bell ♪

379
00:20:51,937 --> 00:20:54,690
[class bell ringing]

380
00:20:57,358 --> 00:20:59,402
♪ Like you I was curious ♪

381
00:20:59,485 --> 00:21:02,405
♪ So innocent
I asked a thousand questions ♪

382
00:21:02,488 --> 00:21:04,574
♪ But unless you want to suffer ♪

383
00:21:04,657 --> 00:21:08,119
♪ Listen up and I will
Teach you a thing or two ♪

384
00:21:08,203 --> 00:21:10,621
♪ You listen here, my dear
You'll be punished so severely ♪

385
00:21:10,705 --> 00:21:13,040
♪ If you step out of line
And if you cry it will be double ♪

386
00:21:13,124 --> 00:21:14,459
♪ You should stay out of trouble ♪

387
00:21:14,542 --> 00:21:17,420
♪ And remember to be extremely careful ♪

388
00:21:18,713 --> 00:21:19,547
Why?

389
00:21:19,630 --> 00:21:21,048
♪ Why? ♪

390
00:21:21,131 --> 00:21:22,007
Why?

391
00:21:22,091 --> 00:21:23,468
Didn't you hear what we said?

392
00:21:24,760 --> 00:21:28,388
[Agatha over PA] I have become aware
that some of you are not yet in class.

393
00:21:28,472 --> 00:21:29,640
Correct this.

394
00:21:29,724 --> 00:21:32,184
You have five seconds to comply.

395
00:21:32,267 --> 00:21:33,352
♪ A-B-C-D-E-F-G ♪

396
00:21:33,435 --> 00:21:34,644
-♪ H-I-J-K-L-M-N-O ♪
-[Agatha] Five.

397
00:21:34,729 --> 00:21:35,688
♪ P-Q-R-S ♪

398
00:21:35,771 --> 00:21:37,022
-♪ T-U-V-W-X ♪
-[Agatha] Four.

399
00:21:37,106 --> 00:21:39,566
-♪ Why, why, why, why, why, why, why? ♪
-[Agatha] Three.

400
00:21:39,649 --> 00:21:41,651
-[Agatha] Two.
-Lavender, Matilda, inside quick.

401
00:21:41,735 --> 00:21:43,487
-One.
-♪ Just you wait for Phys-Ed ♪

402
00:21:46,865 --> 00:21:48,533
Hmm…

403
00:21:48,617 --> 00:21:52,537
Yes, uh, Miss Trunchbull
is keen on punctuality.

404
00:21:52,621 --> 00:21:56,082
Best not to be late.
Now, come and meet your new friends.

405
00:21:56,165 --> 00:21:57,792
This is Lavender and Matilda.

406
00:21:58,377 --> 00:22:00,962
And if there's anything too difficult,

407
00:22:01,546 --> 00:22:02,714
just ask a classmate.

408
00:22:02,797 --> 00:22:04,674
They'll help you. All right?

409
00:22:05,258 --> 00:22:06,843
-Miss!
-Hm?

410
00:22:06,926 --> 00:22:08,469
It's hurting my head.

411
00:22:09,763 --> 00:22:12,265
Oh, no, Nigel, that's not for you.

412
00:22:12,348 --> 00:22:15,518
They use this classroom
for grown-up lessons at night.

413
00:22:15,601 --> 00:22:17,145
They must have left it up there.

414
00:22:17,645 --> 00:22:19,688
[whimpering]

415
00:22:20,648 --> 00:22:23,567
Nigel. Nigel. Nigel.

416
00:22:23,651 --> 00:22:24,735
Nigel.

417
00:22:26,029 --> 00:22:28,822
[whispering] Relax.

418
00:22:30,574 --> 00:22:31,409
Well done.

419
00:22:32,910 --> 00:22:36,079
Now, who would like to
polish off what's on the board?

420
00:22:36,163 --> 00:22:37,623
-Oh, me!
-Miss Honey, me!

421
00:22:39,833 --> 00:22:40,668
Matilda.

422
00:22:41,168 --> 00:22:42,210
How about you?

423
00:22:46,006 --> 00:22:48,884
So… today is reading.

424
00:22:48,967 --> 00:22:50,803
[kids chattering excitedly]

425
00:22:50,886 --> 00:22:54,222
Now, this book
is actually for nine-year-olds…

426
00:22:54,306 --> 00:22:56,516
but you're all doing so well…

427
00:22:56,599 --> 00:22:59,436
that I thought we'd give this a try.

428
00:22:59,519 --> 00:23:02,730
I'd like you all
to read the first chapter.

429
00:23:02,814 --> 00:23:06,401
-Eric, what is a chapter?
-It's a chunk of a story, Miss.

430
00:23:06,484 --> 00:23:08,695
Absolutely perfect, Eric.

431
00:23:08,778 --> 00:23:11,989
What I'm hoping is
that you can all read the first chunk,

432
00:23:12,073 --> 00:23:15,117
then we'll discuss how…

433
00:23:16,994 --> 00:23:19,121
Matilda, what are you doing?

434
00:23:20,206 --> 00:23:23,459
Well, I'm polishing it off.

435
00:23:23,543 --> 00:23:24,919
Like you said.

436
00:23:25,002 --> 00:23:28,840
Oh… No, I meant polish it off.

437
00:23:30,257 --> 00:23:32,468
Is that… correct?

438
00:23:32,969 --> 00:23:33,886
[Matilda] Well, yeah.

439
00:23:33,970 --> 00:23:36,848
And then I thought
I may as well do the rest.

440
00:23:37,473 --> 00:23:38,682
The rest?

441
00:23:39,391 --> 00:23:41,268
You know, the prime numbers.

442
00:23:41,768 --> 00:23:43,854
Where X is the square of AB reoccur.

443
00:23:45,856 --> 00:23:49,067
So I realized they must have done it
knowing it was part of a sequence.

444
00:23:50,777 --> 00:23:52,613
Is maths your favorite thing?

445
00:23:53,239 --> 00:23:55,991
It's okay.
But what I really like is reading.

446
00:23:56,492 --> 00:23:58,410
It's like a holiday in your head.

447
00:23:59,369 --> 00:24:00,746
And do you do that a lot?

448
00:24:01,246 --> 00:24:03,915
Get away from everything.
In books, I mean.

449
00:24:03,999 --> 00:24:06,627
Oh, yeah, I read loads this week.

450
00:24:06,710 --> 00:24:08,712
Loads. In one week?

451
00:24:09,671 --> 00:24:12,257
So, which books did you read this week?

452
00:24:12,340 --> 00:24:15,301
Nicholas Nickleby, Jane Eyre,

453
00:24:15,385 --> 00:24:18,346
Tess of the D'Urbervilles,
Of Mice and Men,

454
00:24:18,429 --> 00:24:19,680
The Lord of the Rings,

455
00:24:20,265 --> 00:24:23,101
Moby Dick, Crime and Punishment,

456
00:24:23,851 --> 00:24:25,228
and…

457
00:24:26,312 --> 00:24:27,605
The Cat in the Hat.

458
00:24:34,194 --> 00:24:36,614
[children chattering]

459
00:24:47,792 --> 00:24:49,251
[sighs deeply]

460
00:24:51,420 --> 00:24:52,797
Don't be pathetic.

461
00:24:54,298 --> 00:24:55,424
[exhales shakily]

462
00:24:57,092 --> 00:24:58,635
-Enter.
-[door opens]

463
00:25:03,057 --> 00:25:05,142
[Agatha] Don't just stand there
like a wet tissue, get on with it.

464
00:25:05,225 --> 00:25:06,310
Yes, yes, sorry.

465
00:25:09,313 --> 00:25:11,856
[hesitantly]
So, Miss Trunchbull, there is…

466
00:25:11,940 --> 00:25:15,444
in my class, a girl
called Matilda Wormwood and--

467
00:25:15,527 --> 00:25:18,279
[Agatha] Matilda Wormwood,
daughter of Mr. Harry Wormwood.

468
00:25:18,362 --> 00:25:19,322
Excellent man.

469
00:25:20,031 --> 00:25:21,783
He warned me about the brat though.

470
00:25:22,784 --> 00:25:25,620
Said she's a real… wart.

471
00:25:25,704 --> 00:25:27,580
No, Headmistress, I don't think--

472
00:25:27,664 --> 00:25:29,791
No. No, you do not.

473
00:25:31,250 --> 00:25:33,169
What is the school motto, Miss Honey?

474
00:25:34,253 --> 00:25:36,047
Bambinatum est Maggitum.

475
00:25:36,130 --> 00:25:40,551
Bambinatum est Maggitum.
"Children are maggots."

476
00:25:40,634 --> 00:25:43,179
Thank you for bringing this one
to my attention.

477
00:25:43,262 --> 00:25:45,806
I shall destroy it in due course.
Good day.

478
00:25:47,308 --> 00:25:51,645
[nervously] Miss Trunchbull, it is my
belief that Matilda Wormwood is a genius.

479
00:25:51,729 --> 00:25:53,856
What? No. No.

480
00:25:53,939 --> 00:25:56,775
Haven't I just told you?
She is a gangster.

481
00:25:56,859 --> 00:26:00,946
She can do maths in her head
that I couldn't do with a calculator.

482
00:26:01,029 --> 00:26:03,198
And the books she's read.

483
00:26:03,281 --> 00:26:07,703
It is my opinion that she should be placed
in the top form with the 11-year-olds.

484
00:26:07,786 --> 00:26:08,787
Immediately.

485
00:26:10,914 --> 00:26:14,084
But what about the rules, Honey?

486
00:26:15,919 --> 00:26:18,338
I believe that Matilda Wormwood is…

487
00:26:19,464 --> 00:26:21,716
an exception to the rules.

488
00:26:23,843 --> 00:26:24,677
An exception?

489
00:26:25,887 --> 00:26:27,096
To the rules?

490
00:26:29,682 --> 00:26:32,226
In my school?

491
00:26:32,309 --> 00:26:34,228
I-- I--

492
00:26:35,187 --> 00:26:37,398
♪ Look at my trophies ♪

493
00:26:37,482 --> 00:26:40,902
♪ See how my trophies
Gleam in the sunlight ♪

494
00:26:40,985 --> 00:26:42,904
♪ See how they shine ♪

495
00:26:42,987 --> 00:26:48,575
♪ What do you think it took to become
English Hammer-Throwing Champion ♪

496
00:26:48,659 --> 00:26:50,744
♪ 1959 ♪

497
00:26:50,828 --> 00:26:54,456
♪ Do you think in that moment
When my big moment came ♪

498
00:26:54,540 --> 00:27:00,003
♪ That I treated the rules
With casual disdain ♪

499
00:27:00,087 --> 00:27:02,881
♪ Well? Like hell! ♪

500
00:27:02,964 --> 00:27:06,218
♪ As I stepped up to the circle
Did I change my plan? ♪

501
00:27:06,302 --> 00:27:07,803
♪ Hmm? What? ♪

502
00:27:08,387 --> 00:27:11,390
♪ As I chalked up my palms
Did I wave my hands? ♪

503
00:27:11,473 --> 00:27:13,016
♪ I did not ♪

504
00:27:13,099 --> 00:27:15,936
♪ As I started my spin
Did I look at the view? ♪

505
00:27:16,019 --> 00:27:18,980
♪ Did I drift off and dream
For a minute or two? ♪

506
00:27:19,064 --> 00:27:21,733
♪ Do you think I faltered
Or amended my rotation? ♪

507
00:27:21,817 --> 00:27:24,152
♪ Do you think I altered
My intended elevation? ♪

508
00:27:25,320 --> 00:27:28,031
♪ As the hammer took off
Did I change my grunt ♪

509
00:27:28,114 --> 00:27:31,034
♪ From the grunt I had practiced
For many a month? ♪

510
00:27:31,117 --> 00:27:34,704
♪ Not a jot nor a dot
Did I stray from the plot ♪

511
00:27:34,787 --> 00:27:38,166
♪ Not a detail of my throw
Was adjusted or forgotten ♪

512
00:27:38,249 --> 00:27:41,794
♪ Not even when the hammer left my hands ♪

513
00:27:41,877 --> 00:27:47,132
♪ And sailed high up
Up above the stands ♪

514
00:27:47,216 --> 00:27:50,260
♪ Did I let myself go? ♪

515
00:27:50,345 --> 00:27:52,722
♪ No, no, no ♪

516
00:27:52,805 --> 00:27:55,808
♪ No, no, no, no, no ♪

517
00:27:55,891 --> 00:27:59,436
[announcer, faintly over PA]
She's done it! She is the best!

518
00:28:00,646 --> 00:28:03,023
[music playing over PA system]

519
00:28:03,858 --> 00:28:08,904
♪ If you want to throw the hammer
For your country ♪

520
00:28:09,821 --> 00:28:14,994
♪ You have to stay inside
The circle all the time ♪

521
00:28:16,453 --> 00:28:21,458
♪ If you want to make the team
You don't need happiness or self-esteem ♪

522
00:28:22,167 --> 00:28:26,463
♪ You just need to keep your feet
Inside the line ♪

523
00:28:26,546 --> 00:28:27,422
Sing, children.

524
00:28:27,506 --> 00:28:29,007
Two, three, four.

525
00:28:29,090 --> 00:28:31,885
[children] ♪ If you want
To throw the hammer ♪

526
00:28:31,968 --> 00:28:34,929
-♪ For your country ♪
-♪ Bambinatum est Maggitum ♪

527
00:28:35,013 --> 00:28:38,099
♪ You have to stay inside the circle ♪

528
00:28:38,182 --> 00:28:39,851
♪ All the time ♪

529
00:28:39,934 --> 00:28:41,435
♪ Maggitum, Maggitum ♪

530
00:28:41,519 --> 00:28:43,813
♪ And if you want to teach success ♪

531
00:28:43,897 --> 00:28:46,190
♪ You don't use sympathy or tenderness ♪

532
00:28:46,274 --> 00:28:47,525
♪ Tenderness ♪

533
00:28:47,608 --> 00:28:52,113
♪ You have to force the little squits
To toe the line ♪

534
00:28:52,196 --> 00:28:53,072
Sing, Jenny!

535
00:28:53,656 --> 00:28:56,117
♪ If you want to throw the hammer ♪

536
00:28:56,200 --> 00:28:59,787
-♪ For your country ♪
-♪ Bambinatum est Maggitum ♪

537
00:28:59,870 --> 00:29:02,331
♪ You have to stay inside the circle ♪

538
00:29:02,415 --> 00:29:04,583
♪ All the time ♪

539
00:29:04,667 --> 00:29:06,251
♪ Maggitum, Maggitum ♪

540
00:29:06,335 --> 00:29:09,463
♪ Circulum est ♪

541
00:29:09,547 --> 00:29:13,008
♪ Deus, Deus ♪

542
00:29:13,091 --> 00:29:18,096
♪ Gloria ♪

543
00:29:18,180 --> 00:29:21,016
[blowing whistle]

544
00:29:23,476 --> 00:29:26,855
♪ I apply just one simple rule ♪

545
00:29:27,856 --> 00:29:32,360
♪ To hammer-throwing, life and school ♪

546
00:29:33,778 --> 00:29:36,906
♪ Life's a ball so learn to throw it ♪

547
00:29:36,989 --> 00:29:40,034
♪ Find the bally line and toe it ♪

548
00:29:40,117 --> 00:29:44,747
♪ And always keep your feet
Inside the line ♪

549
00:29:44,831 --> 00:29:46,123
Now get out.

550
00:29:46,207 --> 00:29:47,917
[spluttering]

551
00:29:50,712 --> 00:29:52,171
[whispering] Wormwood.

552
00:29:53,756 --> 00:29:54,966
Wormwood.

553
00:29:56,676 --> 00:29:59,011
Where are you?

554
00:30:00,262 --> 00:30:02,639
Do you want to hear
about my first day at school?

555
00:30:02,723 --> 00:30:05,852
-Yuck. I'd rather eat vegetables.
-[door opens, shuts]

556
00:30:05,935 --> 00:30:08,770
It's official, I'm a genius!

557
00:30:08,854 --> 00:30:10,772
My losing streak is over.

558
00:30:10,856 --> 00:30:13,734
This fella comes into the lot.
Huge he was.

559
00:30:13,817 --> 00:30:15,944
Great big bear of a man.

560
00:30:16,027 --> 00:30:19,198
And this bear of a man wants a luxury car.

561
00:30:19,281 --> 00:30:21,867
Oh, lovely. But do bears drive?

562
00:30:21,950 --> 00:30:24,119
No. He's not a real bear.

563
00:30:24,202 --> 00:30:25,829
Do you have a luxury car?

564
00:30:25,912 --> 00:30:27,581
-I've got two, boy.
-I'm a girl.

565
00:30:27,664 --> 00:30:30,834
One with a smashed-in front,
and one with a smashed-in back.

566
00:30:30,917 --> 00:30:33,294
All I gotta do is cut them in half,

567
00:30:33,378 --> 00:30:36,506
glue them together
and Bob's your chipmunk.

568
00:30:36,589 --> 00:30:37,799
Daddy's back.

569
00:30:37,883 --> 00:30:38,925
But isn't that illegal?

570
00:30:39,009 --> 00:30:42,387
And sort of, well, wrong?

571
00:30:42,470 --> 00:30:45,306
-[exclaiming]
-What'd he say? Wrong?

572
00:30:46,099 --> 00:30:46,933
Wrong?

573
00:30:48,768 --> 00:30:49,894
Give me that.

574
00:30:51,437 --> 00:30:53,731
The Grapes of-- Idiot!

575
00:30:53,814 --> 00:30:55,608
How can grapes be angry?

576
00:30:55,691 --> 00:30:57,652
Hey? What utter junk!

577
00:30:57,735 --> 00:30:59,362
It's not about grapes.

578
00:30:59,445 --> 00:31:01,155
Back-yakking! The little madam!

579
00:31:01,238 --> 00:31:02,490
I'm not back-yakking!

580
00:31:02,573 --> 00:31:03,658
Don't you back-yak me!

581
00:31:04,241 --> 00:31:06,411
I'll rip this book up in front of you.

582
00:31:06,494 --> 00:31:08,704
-No, it's a library book!
-Go on, do it.

583
00:31:12,124 --> 00:31:14,835
-[gasps]
-[Harry grunting]

584
00:31:14,919 --> 00:31:16,003
Go on.

585
00:31:26,846 --> 00:31:28,307
There!

586
00:31:32,686 --> 00:31:33,895
[Harry straining]

587
00:31:35,063 --> 00:31:36,565
-There!
-[gasps]

588
00:31:37,982 --> 00:31:40,485
Now get to bed, you little bookworm.

589
00:31:47,492 --> 00:31:51,537
♪ Just because you find
That life's not fair ♪

590
00:31:52,914 --> 00:31:58,169
♪ It doesn't mean that you just have to
Grin and bear it ♪

591
00:31:58,962 --> 00:32:03,591
♪ If you always take it on the chin
And wear it ♪

592
00:32:05,551 --> 00:32:08,554
♪ Nothing will change ♪

593
00:32:10,514 --> 00:32:11,849
[alarm ringing]

594
00:32:11,932 --> 00:32:14,643
♪ Even if you're little you can do a lot ♪

595
00:32:14,727 --> 00:32:18,481
♪ You mustn't let a little thing
Like "little" stop you ♪

596
00:32:18,564 --> 00:32:21,650
♪ If you sit around
And let them get on top ♪

597
00:32:21,734 --> 00:32:24,987
♪ You might as well be saying
You think that it's okay ♪

598
00:32:25,070 --> 00:32:26,739
♪ And that's not right ♪

599
00:32:33,787 --> 00:32:37,040
But remember Matilda,
two wrongs don't make a right.

600
00:32:37,124 --> 00:32:39,042
[Harry] Ah, twit face.

601
00:32:39,793 --> 00:32:42,587
[mocking] "It's a library book.
It's a library book."

602
00:32:44,714 --> 00:32:46,174
Gripy little gremlin.

603
00:32:48,426 --> 00:32:49,636
Where's my hat?

604
00:32:51,096 --> 00:32:52,222
Here it is, Dad.

605
00:32:58,936 --> 00:33:00,605
Big stupid.

606
00:33:07,111 --> 00:33:09,656
[children yelling,
chattering indistinctly]

607
00:33:10,907 --> 00:33:14,576
But how do they all fit in there?
Her head's the same size as mine.

608
00:33:14,660 --> 00:33:16,245
Does it hurt, Matilda?

609
00:33:16,328 --> 00:33:19,040
Having all those brains squished in there?

610
00:33:19,623 --> 00:33:21,500
No. They seem to just…

611
00:33:22,418 --> 00:33:23,252
fit in.

612
00:33:23,919 --> 00:33:25,587
Can you do telekenipsis?

613
00:33:26,713 --> 00:33:28,840
It's where you have loads of brains.

614
00:33:28,924 --> 00:33:30,884
They squish out through your eyes,

615
00:33:30,967 --> 00:33:33,554
and you can move things with your mind.

616
00:33:33,637 --> 00:33:35,096
Look, watch this.

617
00:33:38,767 --> 00:33:41,061
[grunting lightly]

618
00:33:53,531 --> 00:33:56,367
It's not good to try to be clever.
Not here.

619
00:33:56,451 --> 00:33:59,620
The Trunchbull hates kids being smart.
She hates it.

620
00:33:59,704 --> 00:34:01,497
Isn't learning what school's for?

621
00:34:01,581 --> 00:34:03,959
This isn't a school. It's a prison.

622
00:34:04,042 --> 00:34:05,418
You don't want to get noticed.

623
00:34:05,501 --> 00:34:07,253
Not by Agatha.

624
00:34:07,337 --> 00:34:10,047
They say she turned one kid inside out.

625
00:34:10,131 --> 00:34:12,300
He had to walk around
in cling film to keep his organs in.

626
00:34:12,383 --> 00:34:14,260
That didn't really happen, Bruce.

627
00:34:14,344 --> 00:34:17,638
But she definitely sat on a year seven
until he was jelly.

628
00:34:17,722 --> 00:34:21,726
She caught Julius Rottwinkle
eating a licorice allsort in class.

629
00:34:21,809 --> 00:34:25,813
She picked him up, swung him around
and chucked him out of the window.

630
00:34:25,896 --> 00:34:26,731
Look.

631
00:34:27,397 --> 00:34:29,734
Teachers don't really throw children.

632
00:34:29,817 --> 00:34:32,111
The big kids are just trying to scare you.

633
00:34:32,194 --> 00:34:33,153
[girl] Scare, is it?

634
00:34:33,863 --> 00:34:36,406
You don't know scared until
you've been in Chokey.

635
00:34:39,994 --> 00:34:41,245
What's Chokey?

636
00:34:44,123 --> 00:34:48,001
♪ There's a place you are sent
If you haven't been good ♪

637
00:34:48,084 --> 00:34:51,004
♪ And it's made of spikes and wood ♪

638
00:34:51,087 --> 00:34:53,465
♪ And it isn't wide enough to sit ♪

639
00:34:53,548 --> 00:34:55,174
♪ And even if you could ♪

640
00:34:55,258 --> 00:34:58,428
♪ There are nails on the bottom
So you'll wish you'd stood ♪

641
00:34:59,012 --> 00:35:02,557
♪ When the hinges creak
And the door is closed ♪

642
00:35:02,641 --> 00:35:05,935
♪ You cannot see squat
Not the end of your nose ♪

643
00:35:06,019 --> 00:35:09,188
♪ And when you scream
You don't know if the sound came out ♪

644
00:35:09,272 --> 00:35:13,692
♪ Or if the scream in your head
Even reached your mouth ♪

645
00:35:17,738 --> 00:35:19,198
[Nigel] Hide me!

646
00:35:19,282 --> 00:35:21,534
Someone poured a can of treacle
on The Trunchbull's chair.

647
00:35:21,617 --> 00:35:23,494
She thinks I did, but I never!

648
00:35:23,577 --> 00:35:25,163
Her knickers stuck to the seat.

649
00:35:25,246 --> 00:35:26,789
[all laughing]

650
00:35:26,872 --> 00:35:27,748
[girl] Silence!

651
00:35:28,374 --> 00:35:30,293
You're going to Chokey, kid.

652
00:35:30,376 --> 00:35:33,211
But that's not right!
He didn't do anything.

653
00:35:33,296 --> 00:35:35,673
Take it from me. The boy's doomed.

654
00:35:35,756 --> 00:35:37,883
Matilda, please help me.

655
00:35:37,966 --> 00:35:39,510
Why not just tell her that…

656
00:35:40,427 --> 00:35:41,344
Okay.

657
00:35:42,262 --> 00:35:43,681
Look, when did this happen?

658
00:35:44,264 --> 00:35:45,683
About 20 minutes ago.

659
00:35:45,766 --> 00:35:46,934
But why?

660
00:35:47,017 --> 00:35:48,811
[whistle blowing]

661
00:35:48,894 --> 00:35:51,146
You'd better hide. Quick, blazers!

662
00:35:51,229 --> 00:35:53,941
-[whistle continues blowing]
-Please don't tell her where I am!

663
00:35:55,650 --> 00:35:57,485
[boy] Run, run!

664
00:35:57,569 --> 00:35:58,445
Hurry up!

665
00:35:59,404 --> 00:36:01,531
[hushed chattering]

666
00:36:02,824 --> 00:36:06,035
-[whistle continue blowing]
-[Lavender squeaking]

667
00:36:07,495 --> 00:36:09,914
-Be still, child!
-[gasps]

668
00:36:13,335 --> 00:36:19,048
What a repellent parade
of imps and hobgoblins,

669
00:36:19,131 --> 00:36:22,468
chitter-chattering away.

670
00:36:23,886 --> 00:36:27,849
Where's the maggot known as Nigel?

671
00:36:27,932 --> 00:36:29,433
[muffled fart]

672
00:36:31,310 --> 00:36:32,979
Over there, under those blazers.

673
00:36:33,062 --> 00:36:35,106
[quiet gasps, groans]

674
00:36:39,943 --> 00:36:41,945
Where he's been for the last hour!

675
00:36:42,863 --> 00:36:43,697
What?

676
00:36:44,531 --> 00:36:45,366
Yeah.

677
00:36:45,449 --> 00:36:49,953
You see, Nigel suffers from a rare
but chronic sleep disorder, narcolepsy.

678
00:36:50,579 --> 00:36:52,581
The condition is characterized
by the sufferer

679
00:36:52,664 --> 00:36:54,750
experiencing bouts of fatigue

680
00:36:54,833 --> 00:36:57,377
and falling asleep without any warning.

681
00:36:57,461 --> 00:37:00,171
He fell asleep and we put him
in the blazers for safety.

682
00:37:01,256 --> 00:37:02,132
Didn't we?

683
00:37:04,259 --> 00:37:05,385
Didn't we?

684
00:37:05,468 --> 00:37:09,139
-[children agreeing enthusiastically]
-[Nigel yawning]

685
00:37:09,222 --> 00:37:11,724
I had the strangest dream, Mum.

686
00:37:12,308 --> 00:37:13,518
I thought I was…

687
00:37:14,560 --> 00:37:16,021
Oh.

688
00:37:16,104 --> 00:37:17,647
Hello, Miss Trunchbull.

689
00:37:22,026 --> 00:37:24,112
[tone chiming on PA system]

690
00:37:24,195 --> 00:37:25,821
[amplified] Amanda Thripp.

691
00:37:25,905 --> 00:37:27,865
[crows cawing]

692
00:37:29,074 --> 00:37:32,537
Y-- y-- yes, Miss Trunchbull?

693
00:37:33,120 --> 00:37:38,918
What have I said about… pigtails?

694
00:37:39,501 --> 00:37:42,004
I hate pigtails.

695
00:37:42,087 --> 00:37:44,589
But my mummy likes them.
She says they make me look pretty.

696
00:37:44,674 --> 00:37:47,051
Well, your mother is a twit!

697
00:37:47,134 --> 00:37:48,886
[sports announcer faintly over PA]
And here she goes!

698
00:37:48,969 --> 00:37:52,014
-Look at that spin!
-[Agatha grunting]

699
00:37:52,097 --> 00:37:53,598
[announcer] Oh, my word!

700
00:37:53,682 --> 00:37:54,934
[children gasping]

701
00:37:55,017 --> 00:37:57,352
[announcer] That's far! That's very…

702
00:37:58,687 --> 00:37:59,938
…and we're there!

703
00:38:00,522 --> 00:38:02,232
[Agatha] Yes! Still got it.

704
00:38:02,982 --> 00:38:06,236
Check and see if that child
is still alive, will you?

705
00:38:08,322 --> 00:38:09,989
[clears throat]

706
00:38:11,366 --> 00:38:13,159
And what is your name?

707
00:38:13,242 --> 00:38:14,077
Matilda.

708
00:38:14,869 --> 00:38:15,954
Matilda Wormwood.

709
00:38:16,037 --> 00:38:20,124
Oh! You're Wormwood, are you?

710
00:38:21,334 --> 00:38:24,253
I like troublemakers, Wormwood.

711
00:38:25,129 --> 00:38:27,215
They make such a lovely sound…

712
00:38:27,799 --> 00:38:30,051
when they snap.

713
00:38:30,759 --> 00:38:32,178
[boy] She's alive!

714
00:38:32,803 --> 00:38:34,930
-[boy 2] Hip, hip!
-[children] Hooray!

715
00:38:35,014 --> 00:38:37,016
-Hip, hip!
-Hooray!

716
00:38:37,100 --> 00:38:39,477
-Hip, hip!
-Hooray!

717
00:38:39,560 --> 00:38:41,312
[all cheering]

718
00:38:42,563 --> 00:38:45,649
[Agatha over PA] Remember, Wormwood,
you can never win.

719
00:38:45,733 --> 00:38:50,070
I promise you that.
And a promise is a promise is a promise.

720
00:38:52,990 --> 00:38:55,534
[Matilda] And so the great day arrived.

721
00:38:55,618 --> 00:38:59,079
The Burning Woman Hurling Through the Air

722
00:38:59,162 --> 00:39:01,581
With Dynamite in Her Hair

723
00:39:01,665 --> 00:39:04,960
Over Sharks and Spiky Objects

724
00:39:05,043 --> 00:39:07,670
Caught by the Man Locked in the Cage.

725
00:39:09,047 --> 00:39:13,426
It was like the entire world
had gathered to see the acrobat

726
00:39:13,510 --> 00:39:18,390
and the escapologist's incredible
death-defying feat.

727
00:39:19,266 --> 00:39:21,393
[plane flying overhead]

728
00:39:21,476 --> 00:39:24,061
[crowd murmuring, chattering indistinctly]

729
00:39:29,776 --> 00:39:30,777
[laughing]

730
00:39:30,860 --> 00:39:33,655
[band playing upbeat music]

731
00:39:47,418 --> 00:39:49,003
[women laughing]

732
00:39:52,089 --> 00:39:54,383
Everything was arranged by…

733
00:39:55,467 --> 00:39:57,928
the acrobat's evil stepsister.

734
00:39:58,512 --> 00:40:02,098
A frightening woman who used to be
an Olympic class hammer thrower.

735
00:40:02,683 --> 00:40:05,894
People whispered that in her dark
and brooding heart,

736
00:40:05,977 --> 00:40:09,606
she resented her stepsister's
success and love.

737
00:40:11,024 --> 00:40:12,400
[cymbal crashes]

738
00:40:12,484 --> 00:40:13,819
Suddenly…

739
00:40:14,736 --> 00:40:16,613
out came the escapologist,

740
00:40:16,697 --> 00:40:18,990
but there was no sign of the acrobat,

741
00:40:19,074 --> 00:40:22,702
and no glimpse at all
of the shiny white scarf she always wore.

742
00:40:23,995 --> 00:40:25,914
Ladies and gentlemen,

743
00:40:26,497 --> 00:40:28,291
boys and girls,

744
00:40:28,374 --> 00:40:31,962
The Burning Woman Hurling Through the Air

745
00:40:32,045 --> 00:40:34,672
With Dynamite in Her Hair

746
00:40:34,755 --> 00:40:37,092
Over Sharks and Spiky Objects

747
00:40:37,175 --> 00:40:39,427
Caught by the Man Locked in the Cage

748
00:40:39,510 --> 00:40:42,555
has been canceled!

749
00:40:42,638 --> 00:40:44,765
[all groaning]

750
00:40:45,558 --> 00:40:48,894
Canceled because my wife is…

751
00:40:49,645 --> 00:40:50,771
pregnant!

752
00:40:51,355 --> 00:40:53,357
-[all gasping]
-Oh, Matilda.

753
00:40:54,984 --> 00:40:58,112
[Matilda] Absolute… silence.

754
00:41:00,405 --> 00:41:03,075
You could have heard a fly burp.

755
00:41:05,660 --> 00:41:07,537
-Then suddenly, the audience…
-[child] Hip, hip!

756
00:41:07,621 --> 00:41:10,874
…jumped to its feet
and roared in appreciation!

757
00:41:10,958 --> 00:41:13,627
[band playing fanfare]

758
00:41:15,212 --> 00:41:16,338
[yapping]

759
00:41:16,421 --> 00:41:18,965
-The great feat was instantly forgotten.
-[laughing]

760
00:41:19,841 --> 00:41:22,344
And the applause went on for over an hour!

761
00:41:25,764 --> 00:41:28,475
Oh, Matilda, that's wonderful!

762
00:41:28,558 --> 00:41:30,685
I love stories that end happily.

763
00:41:31,770 --> 00:41:36,565
Forgotten by everyone
except the acrobat's evil stepsister.

764
00:41:37,942 --> 00:41:42,363
When all had quietened down
she produced a contract!

765
00:41:42,446 --> 00:41:44,240
-[Mrs. Phelps] A contract?
-[feedback squealing]

766
00:41:44,323 --> 00:41:47,451
[over PA] A contract you have signed
to perform this feat.

767
00:41:47,535 --> 00:41:50,454
-And perform this feat, you shall!
-No.

768
00:41:50,538 --> 00:41:53,666
[Matilda and Agatha]
I've paid for the posters, publicity,

769
00:41:53,749 --> 00:41:56,169
the catering, the toilet facilities.

770
00:41:56,252 --> 00:41:58,171
If I give the crowd their money back,

771
00:41:58,254 --> 00:41:59,755
where is my profit?

772
00:42:00,339 --> 00:42:03,216
A contract is a contract is a contract.

773
00:42:03,300 --> 00:42:04,885
My hands are tied.

774
00:42:04,968 --> 00:42:08,180
The Burning Woman Hurling Through the Air

775
00:42:08,263 --> 00:42:10,140
With Dynamite in Her Hair

776
00:42:10,223 --> 00:42:12,893
Over Sharks and Spiky Objects

777
00:42:12,976 --> 00:42:16,188
Caught by The Man Locked in a Cage
will be performed,

778
00:42:16,271 --> 00:42:18,899
and it will be performed this day!

779
00:42:18,982 --> 00:42:21,568
Or off to prison you both shall go!

780
00:42:25,948 --> 00:42:27,865
What… what happened next?

781
00:42:29,576 --> 00:42:30,743
I dunno.

782
00:42:30,827 --> 00:42:32,787
What? How can you not know?

783
00:42:33,496 --> 00:42:36,583
It just comes to me in… fizzes.

784
00:42:36,666 --> 00:42:39,836
Well, could you fizz up
a little bit more for me? Now.

785
00:42:40,420 --> 00:42:42,171
I don't think it works like that.

786
00:42:42,755 --> 00:42:43,923
Of course it doesn't.

787
00:42:44,549 --> 00:42:48,177
-Where is this coming from, Matilda?
-What do you mean?

788
00:42:48,260 --> 00:42:49,887
I mean, it's incredible.

789
00:42:49,971 --> 00:42:52,932
But it's taking rather a dark turn.

790
00:42:53,015 --> 00:42:54,684
Maybe I shouldn't tell you any more.

791
00:42:54,767 --> 00:42:57,228
No, no, no. No.

792
00:42:57,311 --> 00:42:59,355
We must find out how it ends.

793
00:43:00,397 --> 00:43:02,608
All I'm saying is,
is everything all right?

794
00:43:02,691 --> 00:43:03,609
You could tell me.

795
00:43:03,692 --> 00:43:07,154
I'd better go, Mrs. Phelps, Mum's waiting.

796
00:43:07,238 --> 00:43:09,781
She gets so upset when she's away from me.

797
00:43:09,865 --> 00:43:13,327
She says every minute
is like an eternity so…

798
00:43:14,119 --> 00:43:16,622
Is she coming here? Can I meet her?

799
00:43:16,705 --> 00:43:18,164
Bye, Mrs. Phelps!

800
00:43:18,249 --> 00:43:20,542
Matilda, tomorrow I'm at the windmill.

801
00:43:20,626 --> 00:43:22,378
Okay, I'll find you.

802
00:43:24,254 --> 00:43:26,798
[the Wormwoods arguing faintly]

803
00:43:28,592 --> 00:43:30,010
I've got it.

804
00:43:30,093 --> 00:43:32,095
-Harry! Let me have it!
-[clattering]

805
00:43:32,178 --> 00:43:33,972
-[Harry grunting loudly]
-[Mrs. Wormwood yells]

806
00:43:34,055 --> 00:43:35,390
Hang on then.

807
00:43:35,473 --> 00:43:38,268
[both straining]

808
00:43:38,351 --> 00:43:40,436
-[Harry] You're hurting me!
-Yeah. Hold on, hold on.

809
00:43:44,399 --> 00:43:46,234
Let me pull, Harry.

810
00:43:46,317 --> 00:43:47,318
Pull then!

811
00:43:51,030 --> 00:43:53,324
[children chattering]

812
00:44:17,639 --> 00:44:18,473
Matilda.

813
00:44:21,977 --> 00:44:24,354
I believe your mind is extraordinary.

814
00:44:24,896 --> 00:44:27,524
So I'm taking things into my own hands.

815
00:44:28,650 --> 00:44:29,943
Starting tomorrow,

816
00:44:30,026 --> 00:44:32,529
I'm going to bring in a selection
of very clever books.

817
00:44:32,612 --> 00:44:35,114
You can sit and read them
while I teach the others,

818
00:44:35,198 --> 00:44:37,992
and if you have any questions, well…

819
00:44:38,076 --> 00:44:39,786
I shall do my best to answer them.

820
00:44:41,079 --> 00:44:42,288
How does that sound?

821
00:44:45,625 --> 00:44:48,336
[gasps, chuckles]

822
00:44:49,588 --> 00:44:50,755
Matilda…

823
00:44:52,215 --> 00:44:53,842
That is the biggest hug in the world.

824
00:44:55,176 --> 00:44:57,386
You're going to hug all the air out of me.

825
00:44:59,847 --> 00:45:01,890
[Agatha, over PA]
What a touching little scene.

826
00:45:06,229 --> 00:45:07,105
Move!

827
00:45:07,813 --> 00:45:12,901
I believe I said this maggot
was to receive no special treatment.

828
00:45:12,985 --> 00:45:16,238
In fact, I seem to recall informing you

829
00:45:16,322 --> 00:45:21,994
that this particular snot-ball
was evil incarnate, did I not?

830
00:45:22,077 --> 00:45:23,704
No, Miss Trunchbull, Matilda is not--

831
00:45:23,787 --> 00:45:25,497
Did you just say "no," Jenny?

832
00:45:27,082 --> 00:45:27,916
To me?

833
00:45:30,878 --> 00:45:34,256
Matilda Wormwood is a criminal.

834
00:45:35,966 --> 00:45:37,134
[over PA] This morning,

835
00:45:37,217 --> 00:45:41,513
a piece of my private
chocolate cake was stolen.

836
00:45:43,765 --> 00:45:47,394
It is my contention that you performed
this vileness, Wormwood, you.

837
00:45:47,477 --> 00:45:50,021
You have two choices,
admit your guilt and be punished,

838
00:45:50,104 --> 00:45:52,732
or call me a liar… and be punished.

839
00:45:56,027 --> 00:45:57,779
Think very carefully

840
00:45:57,862 --> 00:46:01,198
about what comes out
of your mouth, Wormwood.

841
00:46:01,783 --> 00:46:03,576
I did not stea--

842
00:46:03,660 --> 00:46:06,913
[loud, prolonged belch]

843
00:46:12,459 --> 00:46:14,045
[gasps]

844
00:46:31,144 --> 00:46:32,688
[gasping]

845
00:46:38,026 --> 00:46:39,402
Chocolate.

846
00:46:40,111 --> 00:46:42,447
Bruce Bogtrotter.

847
00:46:44,616 --> 00:46:46,785
[timidly] Yes, Miss Trunchbull?

848
00:46:48,244 --> 00:46:50,580
Thank you, Maurice, that will be all.

849
00:46:51,957 --> 00:46:53,792
[grunting]

850
00:46:53,875 --> 00:46:58,129
Staff dismissed. Come on.
Everybody out. Everybody out, come on.

851
00:46:58,213 --> 00:46:59,130
[Agatha] Move!

852
00:47:11,309 --> 00:47:12,935
You liked my cake…

853
00:47:13,894 --> 00:47:15,020
didn't you, Bruce?

854
00:47:15,104 --> 00:47:18,190
Yes, Miss Trunchbull,
it was very delicious.

855
00:47:18,273 --> 00:47:19,734
So chocolatey.

856
00:47:20,317 --> 00:47:22,194
And I'm really very sorry, I--

857
00:47:22,277 --> 00:47:23,112
No, no…

858
00:47:23,988 --> 00:47:27,241
Just so long as you enjoyed the cake.
That's the main thing.

859
00:47:28,533 --> 00:47:29,368
Is it?

860
00:47:30,911 --> 00:47:32,454
[singsong] Oh, Cook.

861
00:47:50,555 --> 00:47:51,765
[cook coughs]

862
00:47:54,518 --> 00:47:55,351
Be still!

863
00:47:58,437 --> 00:48:00,732
What's the matter, Bogtrotter?
Lost your appetite?

864
00:48:01,274 --> 00:48:04,986
Don't worry… all you have to do
is eat every last crumb.

865
00:48:06,404 --> 00:48:10,366
And if you perform this incredible feat,
I promise you,

866
00:48:10,449 --> 00:48:12,285
all will be forgiven.

867
00:48:12,368 --> 00:48:14,287
[hesitating] Every crumb?

868
00:48:15,413 --> 00:48:17,581
-But I'm full.
-Oh, no, you're not full.

869
00:48:17,665 --> 00:48:21,044
I'll tell you when you're full.
And I say that criminals like you

870
00:48:21,127 --> 00:48:23,629
aren't full until they've
eaten the entire cake.

871
00:48:24,838 --> 00:48:27,716
-But--
-You haven't got time for "buts." Eat.

872
00:48:27,800 --> 00:48:29,302
But I can't eat it all.

873
00:48:29,385 --> 00:48:30,928
Headmistress, he'll be sick.

874
00:48:32,137 --> 00:48:34,723
He should have thought of that
before he made a pact with Satan

875
00:48:34,807 --> 00:48:36,642
and decided to steal my cake.

876
00:48:37,142 --> 00:48:38,977
-Eat.
-[children, whispering] He can't!

877
00:48:39,061 --> 00:48:40,771
-Eat.
-He surely can't!

878
00:48:40,854 --> 00:48:42,564
-Eat!
-He might explode!

879
00:48:42,648 --> 00:48:43,857
Eat!

880
00:48:43,941 --> 00:48:46,985
♪ A single slice
Or even two, Bruce ♪

881
00:48:47,069 --> 00:48:50,823
♪ Might have been nice
But even you, Bruce ♪

882
00:48:50,906 --> 00:48:54,284
♪ Have to admit
Between you and it ♪

883
00:48:54,367 --> 00:48:57,454
♪ There's not a lot
